node.data: Now letst first run it What you see is a console print of 3 times abcdefgh: lowercase, uppercase and randomcase.

Lets analyse the code
a main file rejevenationDemo.c for each to be printed character a separate file a tracer (typical for embedded machine software) the 'business logic' printAlphabet that prints (part of) the alphabet to the console

What is wrong with ths code or needs to be improved
in common.h a new Struct for error handling has been introduced that should replace an obsolete MACRO The functionality to print a char to the console could be generalized. Although this might be difficult to see. Look for example to the different implementations of printA.c and printC.c Throughout the years printing Random case that become unused but is still available everywhere.

Now let's use Renaissance to fix it Renaissance uses a command line tool to take the following steps: To make 'try first then commit' possible it will first reset the code base to the latest version (using a configuration manager like GIT). Then it visits all the files that are part of you code base Per file it performs specified refactorings until finished The developer can see the changes with any diff tool If the change are Okay they can be committed
Let's do the refactoring in steps
Replace all the ERROR_RESULT macro definitions with the ErrorResult struct. Look at errorResult.c.refactor file how it is done. Run rejuvenationDemo It specifies to refactor certain nodes in the AST (abstract syntax tree) Maybe this looks like a search and replace but it is (absolutely) not. But that will become clear later on
Look at printA.c and printA.h for results
Now remove random case as it has become unused throughout the years. This is typically for embedded system where certain sensors or devices are completely removed from the installed base. Look a removeCase.c.refactor for the refactoring rules The call is removed and the char cases are removed Perform the refactoring Look at printA.c and printC.c for results. It shows that we took the opportunity to change 2 different implementations of the same functionality to one
Now clean up
Build the project and notice the warnings. This is typically something that happens when refactoring. After refactoring you need to clean up unused stuff This can be corrected using a post processing refactor file that runs after a function has refactored Look at cleanup.c.refactor for details Run Rejuvenation demo postprocess Rebuild. Notice that the warnings are gone Run and look at the console output
Remove duplicates Now that we have normalised the code it might be a good idea to replace duplicate code with a function printInCase Uncomment removeDuplicate.c.refactor and useFunc.c.refactor Explain removeDuplicates.c.refactor Run Rejuvation demo postprocess

Other cases Renaissance has already been used in several project to refactor bulk changes. These can be simple or even complex cases like for example Clean up unused includes Make header files self contained Replace strcpy by strncpy to fix potential buffer overflows Fix headerguard mismatches (Partial) Language upgrades for instance from C11 to C14 etc...
